        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3268292863" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2350389724564727848">The First Phone Call From Heaven is the third book I’ve read from the very talented Mitch Albom, a New York Times Bestselling Author. This is also my least favorite. Tuesdays With Morrie and The Five People You Meet In Heaven were both more character driven, entertaining and enlightening. Albom’s books do tend to grapple with the human emotions, faith and redemption and; this one was no different, just the least captivating. The First Phone Call From Heaven was intriguing in the beginning, drug </span>
  <span id="freeText2350389724564727848" style="display:none">The First Phone Call From Heaven is the third book I’ve read from the very talented Mitch Albom, a New York Times Bestselling Author. This is also my least favorite. Tuesdays With Morrie and The Five People You Meet In Heaven were both more character driven, entertaining and enlightening. Albom’s books do tend to grapple with the human emotions, faith and redemption and; this one was no different, just the least captivating. The First Phone Call From Heaven was intriguing in the beginning, drug in the middle and then redeemed itself by interesting surprises in the end. I give it 3.5 stars.<br /><br />Standout Quotes:<br />“There are two stories for every life; the one you live and the one others tell.”<br /><br />“Fear is how you lose your life...a little bit at a time....What we give to fear, we take away from...faith.”<br /><br />“If you find one true friend in your life, you’re richer than most. If that one true friend is your husband, you’re blessed.”</span>
